Shelley Graham, member of Tasmania Parks &amp; Wildlife Service, explained to Cnn that the orchestras are continuing to fight: "They try to turn and return to the beach but they can't. It is really hard to see all this.» Many images taken from above show the cetaceans scattered along the beach, some semi-sepolated by sand, others trapped in dry areas and areas where the water is little deep, not far from rocks and rocks. There is a precedent, it still remembers the American broadcaster. In 1974 a pack of 160-170 specimens spread, in a similar way, on the Black River beach and, still today, no known how many specimens survived. The most serious of all, however, dates back to 2020, when about 450 cetaceans were identified. Today the solution is one: suppress animals to avoid unnecessary suffering and minimize their agony. After so many hours spent on the sand, in fact, many of them began to emit strong sounds that emphasize anguish and disorientation.
<div </div
According to experts, moreover, cetaceans in those conditions can survive only for about 6 hours before starting to deteriorate. "It is not often clear why whales are beached," added Angus Henderson, a member of the Institute of Marine and Antarctic Studies of Tasmania. "There are many natural causes such as disease, loss of orientation, weather conditions and even magnetic abnormalities." Usually, in fact, you can try to put in water animals so big with equipment and specific machinery. But this time, to stop operations, it is the conformation of the place, the limited accessibility and the difficulties of displacement and transport. Also because it is a species whose weight oscillates between 500 kilograms and three tons, with a length that can touch the 6 meters.&nbsp;&nbsp; Whales are a species protected in Tasmania&nbsp;> and touching their carcass means committing a crime. &nbsp;&nbsp;<br> &nbsp;
